It's a safe bet that every nuclear reactor in the Western world is ringed with SAMS, fighter patrols, and security measures we can't even guess at. A failed attack could play into our hands, another non-catastrophe like 3 Mile Island. There is another point worth bringing up. <br>
As Yales' wind-crusade over at Project Orion demonstrates, the nuclear fear-profiteers are apparently hoping that any opposition they drum up to nuclear utility power will rub off on any other application of nuclear energy. We also see this in GNAWanPIS, with its Grand Unified Idiot Luddite Theory* of radicalism. I think they are missing something. With the world full of nuclear scientists and engineers, and nuclear materials, there is a great deal of incentive to go ahead with various applications of nuclear energy. The end of the cold war, and the relative perfection of nuclear weapons have closed one avenue of opportunity for them. Eco-wackies are hellbent on closing another by shutting down the nuclear utilities. The nuclear industry will turn increasingly to space applications as a last resort. Ecowackies will correctly declare that this is what is happening, but it won't help them.   <br>
I predict that they will have a hard time selling the public on the idea that nuclear rockets and nuclear power stations represent equivalent hazards. They might be in reality; but the fear-mongers do not run on reality, they run on psychology and perception. For once, these favor our side. A power plant is always there, visible or nearly so, always running; huge, sinister, threatening. A rocket is only working for a short time, then it is gone into outer space, as far away as anything can get. Their usual hyperbole works well with power plants, it makes them look foolish when they apply it to rockets. They failed completely to stop Cassini, despite its 400,000 curies of radioactivity. This is as much as many NERVA reactors worth of enriched uranium, as much as a couple of hundred Orion drive bombs.<br>
<br>
*G.U.I.L.T. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/uprojectorion.showPublicProfile?language=EN>projectorion</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 204<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(2/2/02 2:49 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm8.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=279.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.fas.org/nuke/hew/Usa/Tests/Rwmohawk2.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Terrorists target Nuclear plants</span><hr size=1> I think France is setting a great example. Illustrating the economic advantages of embracing rather than shunning nuclear power. With sensible security and safety standards it is a clean and cheap power source. <br>
Threats from terrorists also apply to poisoning reservoirs and releasing mustard gas in shopping centres. Far more realistic and catastrophic in my opinion. Even if an attack was launched against a nuclear power plant it's doubtful any seriousa damage would result. Such high priority sites have had security beefed up since September 11th. Smuggling cardboard cutters aboard planes at airports which allow 3 inch knives to be taken by passengers is not the same as infiltrating a Government installation. Crashing a plane? No guarantee of success there either. Assuming the airforce didn't shoot it down. <br>
As you say, it has little relevance to off Earth applications of nuclear power. The nuclear fearmongers have been harping on about nuclear plant security since September 11th. Ofcourse their answer to the problem is the dismantlement of all nuclear power stations. What a strange coincidence that they have been bleating about that for years. They will obviously use any turn of events to highlight their tired and ill thought out cause. Their callousness in using the recent terrorist threat to get more publicity is reprehensible. They honestly make me sick. <br>
Instead of admitting they were wrong about nuclear power they still cling to the insane belief that it is evil and must be stopped. I pity the poor pathetic fools. They obviously won't be satisfied until we are all choking on fumes from coal plants built to replace dismantled nuclear ones. Anti-progressives is what they are.    <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/ubestonnet.showPublicProfile?language=EN>bestonnet</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 65<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(2/2/02 10:21 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm8.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=279.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Terrorists target Nuclear plants</span><hr size=1> It might be a good idea if we make sure terrorists get to see the anti-nuke literature (meaning fiction) so that they attack the nuclear palnts instead of actually killing people. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/uyales.showPublicProfile?language=EN>yales</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Lurker</span><br>  Posts: 2<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(2/11/02 1:07 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm8.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=279.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.naturallycurly.com/celebs/temple.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Terrorists target Nuclear plants</span><hr size=1> Wayne said:<br>
&quot;I think France is setting a great example. Illustrating the economic advantages of embracing rather than shunning nuclear power. With sensible security and safety standards it is a clean and cheap power source. &quot;<br>
<br>
I think the opposite is true.<br>
<br>
France hasn't ordered a nuclear plant since the early '90's.<br>
The last one went turnkey back in '99.<br>
<br>
French polls show only a small minority desire any growth in nuclear capacity.<br>
The polls also show only a tiny minority would accept living near a reactor.<br>
<br>
EdF is essentially bankrupted by its uneconomical investment in nuclear power. It is ~30 billion dollars in debt.<br>
<br>
France's dependence on imported oil has not changed in any way. It imports at the same rate as countries without nuclear commitments.<br>
<br>
The French government has started a process to let nuclear capacity slip from the current 75% down to at the most 60%. Any nuclear building would only be only to replace rapidly decaying reactors.<br>
<br>
Yale<br>
<br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/uzaphod4468.showPublicProfile?language=EN>zaphod4468</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>ezOP</span><br>  Posts: 189<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(2/11/02 2:27 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm8.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=279.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.bbc.co.uk/cult/hitchhikers/gallery/images/100/zaphod2.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.website-wisdom.com/graphics/icons/simpsons/nuclear/12.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Terrorists target Nuclear plants</span><hr size=1> France derives 75% of its electricity from nuclear energy. This is due to a long-standing policy to promote energy independence. <br>
<br>
France is the world's largest net exporter of electricity, and gains some A$3.7 billion per year (EUR 2.3 billion) from this.<br>
<br>
France now claims a substantial level of energy independence and almost the lowest cost electricity in Europe. Over 90% of its electricity is nuclear or hydro.<br>
<br>
France is thus the world's largest net electricity exporter, and electricity is France's fourth largest export.<br>
<br>
France's nuclear power program has cost some FF 400 billion (A$ 90 billion) in 1993 currency, excluding interest during construction. Half of this was self-financed by Electricite de France, 8% (FF 32 billion) was invested by the state but discounted in 1981, and 42% (FF 168 billion) was financed by commercial loans. In 1988 medium and long-term debt amounted to FF 233 billion, or 1.8 times EdF's sales revenue. However, by the end of 1998 EdF had reduced this to FF 122 billion, about two thirds of sales revenue (FF 185 billion) and less than three times annual cash flow. Net interest charges had dropped to FF 7.7 billion (4.16% of sales) by 1998.<br>
<br>
